# Issue #86 piece 2 — the contract-violation panic now prints the
# offending binding's runtime value, on top of the piece-1 predicate
# context. This fixture pins the *boxed* repr path: `describe` returns
# a `String`, so its `Real` parameter `b` is stored boxed (`kai_b`),
# not as a raw unboxed scalar. The emitter must forward the value via
# `kai_incref(kai_b)` (boxed local), NOT `box_wrap(..., kair_b)` — a
# raw read here would reference a non-existent `kair_b` and fail to
# compile. The companion `requires_violation_real` fixture pins the
# raw-unboxed path (a pure `Real -> Real` UFn), so the two together
# cover both reprs under both backends (C and LLVM).
#
# Calling `describe` with `b = 0.0` violates `requires b != 0.0`. The
# expected panic carries the piece-1 lines (kind / fn / predicate /
# decl-site) AND the piece-2 value line `argument b was: 0`.
# (`kai_to_string` renders Real via `%g`, so 0.0 prints as `0`.)

fn describe(b: Real) : String
  requires b != 0.0
{
  "reciprocal exists"
}

fn main() : Unit / Stdout {
  let z = 0.0
  Stdout.print(describe(z))
}
